  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 30.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "With the words of David, and of Asaph",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We can scarcely exclude from our thought the impression that loving human reverence for their own past religious helpers of song and music, and enthusiasm for the memory of them, were here glanced at. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The king's and the princes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " supplementary (moreover) injunction and instruction to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the Levites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as to what words they should put on their lips. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Asaph the seer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is the only place in which Asaph is thus distinctly named ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
